  "title": "Swim Test-Case Visualization",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "981aa0f1d366f5c0",
      "text": "As staff members of the Eclipse Foundation, we faced the challenge of automating many of our\nmanual workflows while minimizing the cost of doing so. Having seen similar efforts fail, we\nchose a new design point that we believed would entice more of our stakeholders to participate.\nThis is about that design point and its success-to-date. [http://wiki.eclipse.org/images/2/20/Swim_System_PNSQC_2007_Paper.pdf pdf]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "eb90591afacb290a",
      "text": "Our solution is to script and visualize long running transactions by simulating them\nusing test databases and capturing the output for display. [http://code.fed.wiki/assets/pages/swim-test-case-visualization/Screen%20Shot%202020-03-30%20at%201.28.53%20PM.jpg enlarge]"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "84f6ac04a15de098",
      "text": "<img width=100% src=http://code.fed.wiki/assets/pages/swim-test-case-visualization/Screen%20Shot%202020-03-30%20at%201.28.53%20PM.jpg>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "42ab868436222aa2",
      "text": "The simulation uses as much of the real application code as possible, replacing only the real\ndatabases with test databases, the user input routines with the test scripts, and the browser output\nwith output stored in buffers for post-processing and evaluation. Consequently the simulated\ntransactions are the real transactions and the scripts are testing the real application code and\nbusiness logic."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a75d575a260244bc",
      "text": "Because our transactions can take weeks or months to complete, we obviously run our\nsimulations faster than real time using a simulated clock. The visualizer post-processes the\nresults of the simulation to produce an overview two dimensional picture of the progression of\nthe transaction through time, using a page format inspired by the \"swim lane diagrams\" made\npopular in business process reengineering."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5e157bc69e55d139",
      "text": "The overview contains a\ncolumn of each person involved in the transaction and icons with fly-out details representing\nimportant interactions. This format has worked well for our need, but could easily be substituted\nwith some other format without invalidating the rest of our results or even modification of the\ntest scripts."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c419729eb1e73d41",
      "text": "The simulator and visualizer are used in development and testing, but are also deployed with the\nfinished application as a form of documentation. This use of the tests as documentation has the\nnatural advantage of the documentation being automatically maintained, but it also forces us to\nmake design choices so that the tests actually make good documentation. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "ace8df8f63595c3a",
      "text": "In our previous attempts to provide this same “the tests are the documentation” failed because the tests contained\ntoo much detail to be good documentation; detail that was necessary for testing, but\noverwhelming as documentation in the sense of “can't see the forest for the trees”. Our solution\nhere has a carefully chose set of abstractions that make the scripts both useful as tests and useful\nas documentation."
    }
